{tt+|ro|orez|n}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|рис|m}}\n* Samoan: {{t|sm|alaisa}}\n* Sango: {{t|sg|loso}}\n* Sanskrit: {{tt+|sa|व्रीहि|m}}\n* Santali: {{tt+|sat|ᱫᱟᱠᱟ}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|rus|m}}, {{tt|gd|rìs|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|ри́жа|f}}, {{tt|sh|пѝринач|m}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|ríža|f}}, {{tt+|sh|pìrinač|m}}\n* Shan: {{tt+|shn|ၶဝ်ႈ}}\n* Silesian: {{t|szl|ryż|m}}\n* Sindhi: {{tt|sd|چانور}}\n* Sinhalese: {{tt|si|බත්}} {{q|cooked}}, {{tt|si|හාල්}} {{q|husked, uncooked}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|ryža|f}}\n* Slovene: {{tt+|sl|riž|m}}\n* Somali: {{tt+|so|bariis}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{tt|dsb|rajs|m}}\n* Sotho: {{tt|st|raese}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|arroz|m}}\n* Sundanese: {{tt+|su|béas}}, {{tt+|su|sangu}}\n* Swahili: {{tt+|sw|mpunga}} {{q|raw seed in husk}}, {{tt+|sw|mchele}} {{q|husked seed}}, {{tt+|sw|wali}} {{q|cooked}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|ris|n}}\n* Sylheti: {{tt|syl|ꠗꠣꠘ}} {{q|unpeeled}}, {{tt|syl|ꠌꠣꠃꠟ}} {{q|peeled}}, {{tt|syl|ꠜꠣꠔ}} {{q|peeled and cooked}}\n* Tagalog: {{tt+|tl|bigas}} {{q|raw seed}}, {{tt+|tl|kanin}} {{q|cooked}}\n* Tajik: {{tt+|tg|биринҷ}}\n* Talysh: {{t|tly|bırz}}\n* Tamil: {{tt+|ta|அரிசி}} {{qualifier|uncooked}}, {{tt+|ta|சோறு}} {{qualifier|cooked}}\n*: Old Tamil: {{tt|oty|𑀅𑀭𑀺𑀘𑀺}}\n* Tarantino: {{t|roa-tar|rise|m}}\n* Tarifit: {{tt|rif|aṛṛuẓ}}\n* Tat: {{t|ttt|bürünc}}\n* Tatar: {{tt+|tt|дөге}}\n* Tausug: {{t|tsg|humay}}\n* Telugu: {{tt+|te|వడ్లు}}, {{tt+|te|బియ్యం}} {{q|raw/husked seed}}, {{tt+|te|అన్నము}} {{qualifier|cooked}}\n* Ternate: {{t|tft|bira}}\n* Tetum: {{tt|tet|foos}} {{q|picked}}, {{tt|tet|etu}} {{q|cooked}}\n* Thai: {{tt+|th|ข้าว}}\n* Tibetan: {{tt|bo|འབྲས}}\n* Tocharian B: {{tt|txb|klu}}\n* Tongan: {{t|to|laise}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|pilav}}, {{t+|tr|düğü}}, {{t+|tr|pirinç}}\n* Turkmen: {{tt+|tk|bürünç}}\n* Uab Meto: {{tt|aoz|ane}}\n* Ubykh: {{tt|uby|p̒irinǰ}}\n* Udi: {{tt|udi|бириндз}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt|uk|рис|m}}, {{tt|uk|риж|m}}\n* Urdu: {{tt+|ur|چاوَل|m}}, {{t|ur|بِرَنْج|m}}, {{t|ur|پُلاؤ|m}} {{q|pilaf}}\n* Uyghur: {{t+|ug|گۈرۈچ}}\n* Uzbek: {{tt+|uz|guruch}}\n* Venetan: {{tt|vec|rixo|m}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt+|vi|gạo}}, {{tt+|vi|cơm}} {{q|cooked}}\n* Vilamovian: {{tt|wym|ryź|m}}\n* Volapük: {{tt+|vo|risat}}\n* Waray-Waray: {{tt|war|lu-to}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|reis|m}}\n* Wolof: {{tt|wo|tiep}}\n* Xhosa: {{t|xh|irayisi|c9|c10}}\n* Yiddish: {{tt|yi|רײַז|m|f}}\n* Yoruba: {{t|yo|ìrẹsì}}\n* Zhuang: {{tt|za|haeux}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Hausa: {{t-check|ha|àlbárkà kumbe}}\n* Volapük: {{t+check|vo|risat}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n[[File:Manoomin picking, 1905, Minnesota.jpg|thumb|Some Ojibwe-[[Anishinaabeg]] '''ricing''' on a lake]]\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[squeeze]] through a [[ricer]]; to [[mash]] or make into rice-[[sized]] pieces (especially {{l|en|potato|potatoes}}).\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Miss Parloa's New Cook Book: A Guide to Marketing and Cooking|year=1881|author=Maria Parloa|passage='''Riced''' Potato. Have a flat dish and the colander hot. With a spoon, rub mashed potato through the colander on to the hot dish.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bEIbAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22riced%22%20%22potato%22&pg=PA239#v=onepage&q=%22riced%22%20%22potato%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Potato Chipper|volume=21|page=88|year=1961|passage=Following '''ricing''', the potato mash proceeds to the drum drier where flaking is done.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=As Love Blooms (The Gregory Sisters Book #3): A Novel|author=Lorna Seilstad|year=2015|passage=Last night I '''riced''' the potatoes and added in the cream and butter while they were hot, so today wll we have to do is add flour and roll them out.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[harvest]] [[wild rice]] ({{taxfmt|Zizania|genus}} spp.)\n#* {{quote-journal|en|magazine=Botanical Gazette|page=505|author=John Merle Coulter|year=1894|passage=In northern Minnesota the whites have invented the verb \"to '''rice''',\" and speak of \"'''ricing''',\" i. e., harvesting the crop of wild rice.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xqzzAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22ricing%22%20%22potato%22&pg=PA505#v=onepage&q=%22ricing%22%20%22potato%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Wild rice and the Ojibway people|author=Thomas Vennum|year=1988|passage=When '''ricing''', the Ojibway dress warmly at first; by midday they may shed some clothes as harvest toil combines with the hot sun of late summer to warm them.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=A Capital Place: Reminiscences of a Sandy Lake Boyhood|author=David Laursen|year=2002|passage=As it was, the Indian seldom bothered to harvest wild rice on public waters after opening day of the '''ricing''' season.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-lWtBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PT143&dq=%22ricing%22&pg=PT143#v=onepage&q=%22ricing%22&f=false}}\n# {{lb|en|rare}} To throw rice at a person (usually at a wedding).\n#* {{quote-journal|en|work=The Illustrated London News|volume=89|page=90|date=July 24 1886|passage=So far as I can make out, the idiotic function of “'''ricing'''” English brides and bridegrooms is not twenty years old.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R4o-AQAAMAAJ&dq=%22ricing%22%20%22wedding%22&pg=PA90#v=onepage&q=%22ricing%22%20%22wedding%22&f=false|title=Echoes of the Week}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Gilded Lily|author=Helen Argers|year=2002|passage=The couple was well '''riced''' and sent on their way.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZGqqwgJuSi0C&lpg=PA300&dq=%22riced%22%20%22wedding%22&pg=PA300#v=onepage&q=%22riced%22%20%22wedding%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Billy: A Gay Trilogy|year=2006|author=Timothy Lee|passage=As the reception ended the two newlyweds were '''riced''' to death and fled into an awaiting getaway car and drove off...followed by a stream of tin cans.}}\n# {{lb|en|computing|transitive}} To [[customize]] the [[user interface]] of a [[computer]] system, e.g. a [[desktop environment]]. {{n-g|(derived from {{m|en|rice out}})}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to harvest wild rice}}\n* Ojibwe: {{t|oj|manoominike}}\n* Polish: {{t|pl|[[uprawiać]] [[dziki]] [[ryż]]|impf}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|ris}}, {{m|enm|rys}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hrīs||branch; twig}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hrīsą||bush; twig}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*(s)kreys-||to turn; bend; wind; move; shake}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|reise}}, {{m|sco|rice||twigs; brushwood}}, {{cog|fy|riis}}, {{m|fy|rys}}, {{cog|nl|rijs||little branch; twig; osier; whip}}, {{cog|nds-de|Ries}}, {{cog|de|Reis||twig; sprig; shoot}}, {{cog|sv|ris||twigs; brush; rod}}, {{cog|is|hrís}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|en|rise}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|now chiefly|dialectal|Scotland|Ireland}} A {{l|en|twig}} or {{l|en|stick}}.\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=A systematic treatise on the theory and practice of draining land|author=John Johnstone|year=1834|passage=To guard the bank from the impression of the water, a fence, OF STAKE AND '''RICE''', may be made along the bottom of it next the sea, which will last till the surface on that side is sufficiently swarded, and the mound properly consolidated.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m7FfAAAAcAAJ&dq=%22rice%22%20%22fence%22&pg=PA168#v=onepage&q=%22rice%22%20%22fence%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Book of the Farm|volume=1|author=Henry Stephens|passage=Another form of dead-hedge is the ''stake-and-'''rice''''', and it is formed of the branches of forest trees; and where these are plentiful and thorns scarce, it is an economical dead fence.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QPaJmMSYiFMC&dq=%22fence%22%20%22rice%22&pg=PA579#v=onepage&q=%22fence%22%20%22rice%22&f=false|year=1851}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|magazine=Notes and Queries|series=6|volume=6|date=July 16 1881|passage=\"Gilbert White, the well-known naturalist, in a letter dated Selborne, Oct. 4th, 1775, says, 'Our people here, you know, call coppice-wood or hedge-wood '''''rice''''' or '''''rise'''''. Is this word still in use in that neighbourhood? And is it also known in Surrey?\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MuU1AQAAMAAJ&dq=%22hedge%22%20%22ryce%22&pg=PA53#v=onepage&q=%22hedge%22%20%22ryce%22&f=false}}\n# {{lb|en|weaving|obsolete}} A {{l|en|bobbin}} or {{l|en|spool}}.\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Middlesex County Records|year=1892|passage={{...}} taken unlawfully from the same house five \"machines called 'Engine-Weaving Loomes' worth thirty pounds, and two ounces of silke worth five shillings, and two joynt-stooles worth three shillings, and a pair of ''''Rices''' to wind silke on' worth four shillings {{...}}|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AI4NAAAAIAAJ&dq=%22rices%22%20%22weaving%22&pg=PR29#v=onepage&q=%22rices%22%20%22weaving%22&f=false|editor=John Cordy Jeaffreson|volume=4}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Cotton Weaving: Its Development, Principles, and Practice|author=Richard Marsden|year=1895|passage=The hanks are placed upon light, collapsible hexagon reels termed '''rices''', which are easily lifted out of their position for the reception of the hank.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wLJLAAAAIAAJ&dq=%22rices%22%20%22weaving%22&pg=PA272#v=onepage&q=%22rices%22%20%22weaving%22&f=false}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Hand weaving and cloth design|author=Marianne Straub|year=1977|passage=Swift ('''rice''') Skein holder, hank holder.}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|rise-wood}}/{{l|en|risewood}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=ceir|ERIC|Eric|cire|eric|icer}}\n\n{{C|en|Foods|Oryzeae tribe grasses|Grains}}\n\n==Lower Sorbian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|dsb|/ˈrʲit͡sɛ/|[ˈrʲit͡sə]}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|dsb|verb form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|dsb|ricaś||3|p|pres}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Adjective====\n{{head|enm|adjective|altform=1}}\n\n# {{tlb|enm|Early ME}} {{alt form|enm|riche|t=rich|id=rich}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}}\n\n# {{tlb|enm|Early ME}} {{alt form|enm|riche|t=realm|id=realm}}\n\n==Old English==\n{{was fwotd|ang|2013|October|29}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|ang|rīc}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{dercat|ang|gem-pro|cel-pro|inh=1}}\nFrom {{inh|ang|gmw-pro|*rīkī|t=kingdom, realm|id=kingdom}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{ang-IPA|rīċe}}\n* {{rhymes|ang|iː.t͡ʃe|s=2}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{ang-noun|n|head=rīċe}}\n\n# {{senseid|ang|kingdom}} [[kingdom]], [[empire]]\n#: {{ux|ang|Rōmāna '''rīċe'''|the Roman '''Empire'''}}\n#: {{ux|ang|Godes '''rīċe'''|the '''Kingdom''' of God}}\n#* '''late 10th century''', [[w:Ælfric of Eynsham|Ælfric]], [https://archive.org/details/aelfricslivesof01aelf/page/218/mode/2up \"Chair of Saint Peter\"]\n#*: {{quote|ang|...and se gramlica casere dioclytianus is gedon of his '''rice'''...|...and the furious emperor Diocletian is deposed from his '''empire''',...}}\n# [[reign]]\n#* [https://archive.org/details/anglosaxonchroni01thor/page/80/mode/1up The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]\n#*: {{quote|ang|''<small>An. DCCLII</small> Hēr Cūðrēd ġefeaht þȳ XII ġēare his '''rīċes''' æt Beorhforda wiþ Æþelbald.''|<small>Year 752</small> In this year, the twelfth year of his '''reign''', Cuthred fought with Athelbald at Burford.}}\n# [[authority]], [[dominion]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ang-decl-noun-ja-n|rīċ}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|ang\n|abbodrīċe<t:abbacy>\n|bisċoprīċe<t:diocese>\n|cynerīċe<t:kingdom>\n|ēastrīċe<t:eastern part of a country>\n|ēþelrīċe<t:native realm>\n|fiþerrīċe<t:tetrarchy>\n|Francrīċe<t:France>\n|heofonrīċe<t:kingdom of heaven>\n|rīċedōm<t:dominion>\n|ricsian<t:to rule, prevail>\n|Rōmāna rīċe<t:Roman Empire>\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|ang|rīċen}}\n* {{l|ang|ricsian}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|enm|riche|id=realm|alts=1}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{dercat|ang|gem-pro|cel-pro|inh=1}}\nFrom {{inh|ang|gmw-pro|*rīkī|t=mighty, rich|id=mighty}}.\n\n====Adjective====\n{{ang-adj|rīċe|sup=riċost}}\n\n# {{senseid|ang|rich}} [[rich]]\n# [[powerful]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ang-adecl|rīċe}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desctree|enm|riche|id=rich}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|ang|rīcsian}}\n\n{{topics|ang|Politics|Imperialism}}\n{{topics|ang|Wealth}}\n\n==Old French==\n\n===Adjective===\n{{fro-adj|mf}}\n\n# {{lb|fro|Picardy}} {{alternative form of|fro|riche}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|es|verb form}}\n\n# {{es-verb form of|rizar}}"}}